quarkusio/quarkus#50618.body:
### Describe the bug

Qute generator generates an incorrect resolver for multiple namespace extension methods _with the same name, number of params but different param types_.

Reproducer: https://github.com/suchwerk/qute-method-overloading-resolution

Also discussed on Zulip: https://quarkusio.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/187030-users/topic/Qute.20template.20extension/with/271565021

There is a workaround where it's possible to keep the method names - each extension method must define a different priority, i.e. something like:
```java
@TemplateExtension(namespace = "my")
public class MyExtensions {

    static String someFunctionName(Number a, Number b) {
        return "Number, Number";
    }

    @TemplateExtension(namespace = "my", priority = 6)
    static String someFunctionName(String a, String b) {
        return "String, String";
    }

    @TemplateExtension(namespace = "my", priority = 7)
    static String someFunctionName(String a, Number b) {
        return "String, Number";
    }
}
```

quarkusio/quarkus#50755.body:
### Describe the bug

When implementing a REST service (resource) that uses a **JAX-RS sub-resource**, 
and you inject a `@RestClient` either in the main resource or in the sub-resource,
the service always responds with **“405 Method Not Allowed”**.


### Expected behavior

When implementing a REST service (resource) that uses a **JAX-RS sub-resource**, 
and you inject a `@RestClient` either in the main resource or in the sub-resource,
the service should respond with **“200 OK”**.

### Actual behavior

I have the following REST Resource:

```
@RequestScoped
@Path("/bugs")
public class BugsResource {

  @Inject
  BugsSubResource bugsSubResource;

  @PermitAll
  @Path("/sub")
  public BugsSubResource works() {
    return bugsSubResource;
  }
}
```
with the following subresource
```
@Dependent
public class BugsSubResource {

  /**
   * This injection of a rest client causes a failure.
   * http://localhost:8080/bugs/sub results in: 405 Method Not Allowed
   */
  @Inject
  @RestClient
  MyRemoteService myRemoteService;

  @GET
  public String hello() {
    return "Hello from Quarkus REST";
  }

}
```

Because of the injection of MyRemoteService (not used in the example), the REST Request
```
curl -v http://localhost:8080/bugs/sub
```
results in 405 Method Not Allowed.

### How to Reproduce?

To illustrate the bug I have created the following github project:
https://github.com/lorenzoni/quarkus-resteasybug

1. git clone git@github.com:lorenzoni/quarkus-resteasybug.git
2. cd quarkus-resteasybug
3. mvn quarkus:dev
4. curl -v http://localhost:8080/bugs/sub

### Output of `uname -a` or `ver`

Linux jupiter 6.8.0-85-generic #85~22.04.1-Ubuntu SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Fri Sep 19 16:18:59 UTC 2 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux

### Output of `java -version`

openjdk version "21.0.3" 2024-04-16 LTS

### Quarkus version or git rev

3.27.0 and also 3.28.5

### Build tool (ie. output of `mvnw --version` or `gradlew --version`)

Apache Maven 3.9.11

### Additional information

The issue originates in the class `ResteasyReactiveProcessor` within the Maven module `quarkus-rest-deployment`.

A performance optimization was introduced in this class:

```java
// Provides a predicate for filtering classes/methods that have annotations from one of the client
// packages. This only reduces the false positives as a "base" interface could be derived and
// client-related annotation applies. Although it seems unlikely that an endpoint without any
// client annotations violates the specification for server resources methods; this type of false
// positive would only mean needless processing as there would be no exception thrown.
```

For class filtering, the method
`classInfo.annotations().stream().anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)`
is used.

However, this method returns **all annotations used anywhere within the resource class**,
instead of **only the annotations that are present at the class level**.

ResteasyReactiveProcessor:

```
          if (classInfo.annotations().stream().anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)
                            || method.annotations().stream().anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)
                            || method.parameters().stream().flatMap(p -> p.annotations().stream())
                                    .anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)) {
                        continue;
          }
```

should be


classInfo.asClass().declaredAnnotations()

```
          if (classInfo.asClass().declaredAnnotations().stream().anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)
                            || method.annotations().stream().anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)
                            || method.parameters().stream().flatMap(p -> p.annotations().stream())
                                    .anyMatch(knownClientAnnotation)) {
                        continue;
          }
```

