I think what looked like a narrow corner case in `ArcContainerImpl#precomputeBeanRawTypes()` may actually happen in the wild when, for instance, you have an application with a lot of entities and you are using the `Repository` pattern for Panache.
You end up with a lot of beans of the exact same raw type, which leads to a massive inefficiency in this method (in the app I'm testing, it represents `5%` of the CPU startup time).

```java
                // we don't expect large lists so this should be fine performance wise
                if (match.contains(bean)) {
                    continue;
                }
```
with `match` being an `ArrayList`.

